> For this recipe, we took classic Mexican ingredients and played with the presentation to create something that's as tasty to the eye as it is to the tongue. Consider it a savory version of a Napoleon!

Wash and dry all produce. Preheat the oven to 400 degrees. Halve, peel, and
finely dice the @red onion{1}(peeled and finely diced). Core, seed, and finely
dice the @yellow bell peppers{1}(cored, seeded, and finely diced). Drain and
rinse the @black beans{1%box}. Roughly chop the @cilantro{¼%ounce}(roughly chopped) leaves and stems. Roughly chop the
@oregano{¼%ounce}(roughly chopped) leaves, then discard the stems. Halve the @lime{1}.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon} in a large #pan over medium heat. Add
half the red onion, half the bell pepper, and cook, tossing for
~{4-5%minutes}, until softened. Stir in the @diced tomatoes{1%box},
oregano, half the black beans, and @sugar{½%teaspoon}. Season generously with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Reduce the heat to low.

In a #medium bowl, combine the remaining black beans, remaining bell pepper,
half the cilantro, and as much red onion as you like. Stir in the juice of
half a lime and a drizzle of oil. Season with salt and pepper.

Toast the tortillas: Place the @flour tortilla{4} on a #baking sheet{} and place
in the oven for ~{3-5%minutes}, until slightly crispy. Stir the remaining
cilantro (reserving a pinch for the guacamole) into the tomato ragu.

Halve, pit, and scoop the @avocado{1}(halved and pitted) flesh into a
#small bowl{}. Add a squeeze of lime juice and a pinch of cilantro. Mash with a
#fork until smooth. Season to taste with salt and pepper.

Assemble: Start assembling the Mexican tortilla stacks in this order: tortilla,
tomato ragu, black bean salsa, and guacamole. Repeat to make a second layer.
Any leftover fillings can be enjoyed on the side. Enjoy!